30 [Alcoholism and Drug Services] and Substance Use Account in the General Fund to be paid
31 monthly as provided in ORS 430.380.
32 (3) If the amount of revenues received from the taxes imposed by ORS 473.030 for the preceding
33 month was reduced as a result of credits claimed under ORS 473.047, the commission shall compute
34 the difference between the amounts paid or transferred as described in subsections (1)(b), (c) and (d)
35 and (2) of this section and the amounts that would have been paid or transferred under subsections
36 (1)(b), (c) and (d) and (2) of this section if no credits had been claimed. The commission shall direct
37 the Oregon Department of Administrative Services to pay or transfer amounts equal to the differ-
38 ences computed for subsections (1)(b), (c) and (d) and (2) of this section from the General Fund to
39 the recipients or accounts described in subsections (1)(b), (c) and (d) and (2) of this section.
40 (4) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, no city or county shall receive for any fiscal
41 year an amount less than the amount distributed to the city or county in accordance with ORS
42 471.350 (1965 Replacement Part), 473.190 and 473.210 (1965 Replacement Part) and this section dur-
43 ing the 1966-1967 fiscal year unless the city or county had a decline in population as shown by its
44 census. If the population declined, the per capita distribution to the city or county shall be not less
45 than the total per capita distribution during the 1966-1967 fiscal year. Any additional funds required
[20]

HB 4070
1 to maintain the level of distribution under this subsection shall be paid from funds credited under
2 subsection (1)(a) of this section.
3 (5) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, amounts to be distributed from the Oregon
4 Liquor and Cannabis Commission Account that are attributable to a per bottle surcharge imposed
5 by the Oregon Liquor and Cannabis Commission, shall be credited to the General Fund.
6 SECTION 24. ORS 430.560 is amended to read:
7 430.560. (1) The Oregon Health Authority shall adopt rules to establish requirements, in ac-
8 cordance with ORS 430.357, for drug treatment programs that contract with the authority and that
9 involve:
10 (a) [Detoxification] Withdrawal management; and
11 (b) [Detoxification] Withdrawal management with acupuncture and counseling[; and]
12 [(c) The supplying of synthetic opiates to such persons under close supervision and control. How-
13 ever, the supplying of synthetic opiates shall be used only when detoxification or detoxification with
14 acupuncture and counseling has proven ineffective or upon a written request of a physician licensed
15 by the Oregon Medical Board or a naturopathic physician licensed by the Oregon Board of
16 Naturopathic Medicine showing medical need for synthetic opiates. A copy of the request must be in-
17 cluded in the client’s permanent treatment and releasing authority records].
18 (2) [Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, synthetic opiates] Medication for opioid use
19 may be made available to a pregnant woman with her informed consent without prior resort to the
20 treatment programs described in subsection (1)[(a) and (b)] of this section.
21 SECTION 25. ORS 430.315, 430.345, 430.368, 430.565 and 430.634 are repealed.
22 SECTION 26. ORS 430.306 is amended to read:
23 430.306. As used in ORS 430.262, [430.315,] 430.335, 430.342, 430.397, 430.399, 430.401, 430.402,
24 430.420 and 430.630, unless the context requires otherwise:
25 (1) “Alcoholic” means any person who has lost the ability to control the use of alcoholic
26 beverages, or who uses alcoholic beverages to the extent that the health of the person or that of
27 others is substantially impaired or endangered or the social or economic function of the person is
28 substantially disrupted. An alcoholic may be physically dependent, a condition in which the body
29 requires a continuing supply of alcohol to avoid characteristic withdrawal symptoms, or
30 psychologically dependent, a condition characterized by an overwhelming mental desire for contin-
31 ued use of alcoholic beverages.
32 (2) “Detoxification center” means a publicly or privately operated profit or nonprofit facility
33 approved by the Oregon Health Authority that provides emergency care or treatment for alcoholics
34 or drug-dependent persons.
35 (3) “Director of the treatment facility” means the person in charge of treatment and rehabili-
36 tation programs at a treatment facility.
37 (4) “Drug-dependent person” means one who has lost the ability to control the personal use of
38 controlled substances or other substances with abuse potential, or who uses such substances or
39 controlled substances to the extent that the health of the person or that of others is substantially
40 impaired or endangered or the social or economic function of the person is substantially disrupted.
41 A drug-dependent person may be physically dependent, a condition in which the body requires a
42 continuing supply of a drug or controlled substance to avoid characteristic withdrawal symptoms,
43 or psychologically dependent, a condition characterized by an overwhelming mental desire for con-
44 tinued use of a drug or controlled substance.
45 (5) “Halfway house” means a publicly or privately operated profit or nonprofit, residential fa-
[21]

HB 4070
1 cility approved by the authority that provides rehabilitative care and treatment for alcoholics or
2 drug-dependent persons.
3 (6) “Local planning committee” means a local planning committee for alcohol and drug pre-
4 vention and treatment services appointed or designated by the county governing body under ORS
5 430.342.
6 (7) “Police officer” means a member of a law enforcement unit who is employed on a part-time
7 or full-time basis as a peace officer, commissioned by a city, a county or the Department of State
8 Police and responsible for enforcing the criminal laws of this state and any person formally
9 deputized by the law enforcement unit to take custody of a person who is intoxicated or under the
10 influence of controlled substances.
11 (8) “Sobering facility” means a facility that meets all of the following criteria:
12 (a) The facility operates for the purpose of providing to individuals who are acutely intoxicated
13 a safe, clean and supervised environment until the individuals are no longer acutely intoxicated.
14 (b) The facility contracts with or is affiliated with a treatment program or a provider approved
15 by the authority to provide addiction treatment, and the contract or affiliation agreement includes,
16 but is not limited to, case consultation, training and advice and a plan for making referrals to ad-
17 diction treatment.
18 (c) The facility, in consultation with the addiction treatment program or provider, has adopted
19 comprehensive written policies and procedures incorporating best practices for the safety of
20 intoxicated individuals, employees of the facility and volunteers at the facility.
21 (d) The facility is registered with the Oregon Health Authority under ORS 430.262.
22 (9) “Treatment facility” includes outpatient facilities, inpatient facilities and other facilities the
23 authority determines suitable and that provide services that meet minimum standards established
24 under ORS 430.357, any of which may provide diagnosis and evaluation, medical care, detoxification,
25 social services or rehabilitation for alcoholics or drug-dependent persons and which operate in the
26 form of a general hospital, a state hospital, a foster home, a hostel, a clinic or other suitable form
27 approved by the authority.
28 SECTION 27. ORS 430.401 is amended to read:
29 430.401. A police officer, person acting under the authority of a mobile crisis intervention team
30 as defined in ORS 430.626, physician, naturopathic physician, physician associate, nurse practitioner,
31 judge, treatment facility, treatment facility staff member or sobering facility, or the staff of the so-
32 bering facility, may not be held criminally or civilly liable for actions pursuant to ORS [430.315,]
33 430.335, 430.397 to 430.401 and 430.402 provided the actions are in good faith, on probable cause and
34 without malice.
35 SECTION 28. ORS 137.300 is amended to read:
36 137.300. (1) The Criminal Fine Account is established in the General Fund. Except as otherwise
37 provided by law, all amounts collected in state courts as monetary obligations in criminal actions
38 shall be deposited by the courts in the account. All moneys in the account are continuously appro-
39 priated to the Department of Revenue to be distributed by the Department of Revenue as provided
40 in this section. The Department of Revenue shall keep a record of moneys transferred into and out
41 of the account.
42 (2) The Legislative Assembly shall first allocate moneys from the Criminal Fine Account for the
43 following purposes, in the following order of priority:
44 (a) Allocations for public safety standards, training and facilities.
45 (b) Allocations for criminal injuries compensation and assistance to victims of crime and chil-
[22]

HB 4070
1 dren reasonably suspected of being victims of crime.
2 (c) Allocations for the forensic services provided by the Oregon State Police, including, but not
3 limited to, services of the Chief Medical Examiner.
4 (d) Allocations for the maintenance and operation of the Law Enforcement Data System.
5 (3) After making allocations under subsection (2) of this section, the Legislative Assembly shall
6 allocate moneys from the Criminal Fine Account for the following purposes:
7 (a) Allocations to the Law Enforcement Medical Liability Account established under ORS
8 414.815.
9 (b) Allocations to the State Court Facilities and Security Account established under ORS 1.178.
10 (c) Allocations to the Department of Corrections for the purpose of planning, operating and
11 maintaining county juvenile and adult corrections programs and facilities and drug and alcohol
12 programs.
13 [(d) Allocations to the Oregon Health Authority for the purpose of grants under ORS 430.345 for
14 the establishment, operation and maintenance of alcohol and drug abuse prevention, early intervention
15 and treatment services provided through a county.]
16 [(e)] (d) Allocations to the Oregon State Police for the purpose of the enforcement of the laws
17 relating to driving under the influence of intoxicants.
18 [(f)] (e) Allocations to the Arrest and Return Account established under ORS 133.865.
19 [(g)] (f) Allocations to the Intoxicated Driver Program Fund established under ORS 813.270.
20 [(h)] (g) Allocations to the State Court Technology Fund established under ORS 1.012.
21 (4) It is the intent of the Legislative Assembly that allocations from the Criminal Fine Account
22 under subsection (3) of this section be consistent with historical funding of the entities, programs
23 and accounts listed in subsection (3) of this section from monetary obligations imposed in criminal
24 proceedings. Amounts that are allocated under subsection (3)(c) of this section shall be distributed
25 to counties based on the amounts that were transferred to counties by circuit courts during the
26 2009-2011 biennium under the provisions of ORS 137.308, as in effect January 1, 2011.
27 (5) Moneys in the Criminal Fine Account may not be allocated for the payment of debt service
28 obligations.
29 (6) The Department of Revenue shall deposit in the General Fund all moneys remaining in the
30 Criminal Fine Account after the distributions listed in subsections (2) and (3) of this section have
31 been made.
32 (7) The Department of Revenue shall establish by rule a process for distributing moneys in the
33 Criminal Fine Account. The department may not distribute more than one-eighth of the total
34 biennial allocation to an entity during a calendar quarter.
35 SECTION 29. ORS 430.370 is amended to read:
36 430.370. (1) A county may provide alcohol and drug abuse prevention, early intervention and
37 treatment services by contracting therefor with public or private, profit or nonprofit agencies. A
38 county entering into such a contract shall receive grants under ORS 430.345 to 430.380 only if the
39 contracting agency [meets the requirements of ORS 430.345 or] is a sobering facility registered under
40 ORS 430.262.
41 (2) A city and county, or any combination thereof, may enter into a written agreement, as pro-
42 vided in ORS 190.003 to 190.620, jointly to establish, operate and maintain alcohol and drug abuse
43 prevention, early intervention and treatment services.
